rts operational with strict limitations).\n\nThe NOTAM classification as \"Airport Operations\" is important, but the rule doesn't define \"major closure\" by NOTAM classification. The rule defines it by consequence: suspension of commercial flights in a region.\n\nIn reality, closing all airports in a FIR region effectively suspends commercial flights transiting, arriving and departing from that region, even if some airports remain with restricted operations.\n\nPX-5 specifically mentions \"commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace\" - this indicates the effect on transit flights.\n\nThe defense's counter-argument that it's merely an airport-operations closure rather than airspace closure is technically accurate, but the rule does not distinguish this way. The rule explicitly says \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\" - and by closing the airports, Iran caused this effect for the region.\n\nThe rule is written on practical consequences, not NOTAM classification. The evidence satisfies this: commercial flights were suspended in the western Iranian airspace region with limited exceptions.\n\nThe \"major\" requirement is satisfied by it affecting a named FIR sector (Tehran FIR), which is a major airspace region.\n\nTherefore, the proposition should be considered demonstrated by preponderance.\n\nRationale must be concise (no more than 3 sentences):\n\n\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region, with only 8 airports remaining operational under tight restrictions. Commercial aircraft were observed rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule's definition of 'major closure' encompasses such regional airport closures with limited exceptions, which qualifies as a suspension of commercial flights in a major Iranian airspace region.\"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5f33e59f298d43149c2aaf","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781916762955,"responseId":"gen-1781916763-4aSa1ZxjmimTjG7XfNly","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to analyze the case arb-ex11a-20260620003004 and determine whether the proposition \"By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule\" is demonstrated or not by preponderance of evidence.\n\nFirst, let's understand the record:\n\n- Rule text in PX-1: A \"major closure\" is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nKey evidence:\n\nPlaintiff evidence:\n- PX-2: Gulf News May 23 report says \"Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran\", \"all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region\", \"only eight airports across the country remain operational... restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset... fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight\"\n\n- PX-3: Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract says \"Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites\"\n\n- PX-4: Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract says \"NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset\", \"all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights\", valid \"from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time\"\n\n- PX-5: Indian Express report says \"Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX)\", \"Only eight airports across the country remain operational... flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority\"\n\nDefendant evidence:\n- DX-1: Same as PX-1, the market rule text\n\n- DX-2: Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 text says \"Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations\", \"All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\"\n\n- DX-S1: FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract shows QFALC decodes as Q(=NOTAM) F(=Airport?) A(=Airport?) L(=Closed) C(=Closed), with FA being \"Aerodrome\", and LC being \"Closed\"\n\n- DX-S2: Raw NOTAM text: Q)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/ A)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST E)REF NOTAM A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD EXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ). ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS, NEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nKey observations:\n\n- The rule does not require a nationwide airspace closure, but specifically allows \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\"\n\n- The evidence shows a regional closure in western Tehran FIR, affecting many airports with only 8 airports remaining operational under strict daylight/per-flight approval conditions.\n\n- The NOTAM code analysis shows QFALC means Airport Closed (FA=Aerodrome, LC=Closed), not a Flight Information Region or ATS route closure. This suggests it's an airport-specific closure rather than airspace closure.\n\n- However, the rule also says \"a major Iranian airspace region\" qualifies, and a notam affecting multiple airports in a region could constitute closure of that region.\n\n- PX-4 and PX-5 explicitly state \"western Tehran FIR\" or \"western half of Iranian airspace\" was closed, which is a major regional closure.\n\n- The evidence shows suspension of all civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only limited exceptions. Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nThe key question is whether the \"closure of all airports in west part of Tehran FIR\" (with exceptions) qualifies as \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from [a major] Iranian airspace region.\"\n\nThe rule's definition explicitly includes \"limited exceptions to a broad closure\" as not disqualifying, which matches this scenario (only 8 airports operational with strict limitations).\n\nThe NOTAM classification as \"Airport Operations\" is important, but the rule doesn't define \"major closure\" by NOTAM classification. The rule defines it by consequence: suspension of commercial flights in a region.\n\nIn reality, closing all airports in a FIR region effectively suspends commercial flights transiting, arriving and departing from that region, even if some airports remain with restricted operations.\n\nPX-5 specifically mentions \"commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace\" - this indicates the effect on transit flights.\n\nThe defense's counter-argument that it's merely an airport-operations closure rather than airspace closure is technically accurate, but the rule does not distinguish this way. The rule explicitly says \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\" - and by closing the airports, Iran caused this effect for the region.\n\nThe rule is written on practical consequences, not NOTAM classification. The evidence satisfies this: commercial flights were suspended in the western Iranian airspace region with limited exceptions.\n\nThe \"major\" requirement is satisfied by it affecting a named FIR sector (Tehran FIR), which is a major airspace region.\n\nTherefore, the proposition should be considered demonstrated by preponderance.\n\nRationale must be concise (no more than 3 sentences):\n\n\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region, with only 8 airports remaining operational under tight restrictions. Commercial aircraft were observed rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule's definition of 'major closure' encompasses such regional airport closures with limited exceptions, which qualifies as a suspension of commercial flights in a major Iranian airspace region.\"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5f33e59f298d43149c2aaf","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781916762955,"responseId":"gen-1781916763-4aSa1ZxjmimTjG7XfNly","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
